snippet.textDisplay: I'm not sure if I'm on the spectrum or not (it could be ADHD but I don't have $2000 to just spend on a test) but I definitely have sensory overload a lot, which can feel like a panic attack, but it's more of a meltdown where I can't control myself. One of the main things is actually those bars that you have to walk though going in and out of libraries, because they make this really high pitched sound that not very many people can hear. Also, certain fabrics and clothing styles bother me, and food textures also. I used to hate avocado because it's so slimy, but then I tried it in sushi, and as a salad dressing because I was told avocados are healthy. The important thing is listen to your body, and to your friends. And always carry a stim/fidget toy and headphones. I don't leave the house without my Power Beats since they're noise isolating and don't have annoying cords.

snippet.textDisplay: I take Autism to the heart because my little siblings are autistic. It’s so sad how people automatically judge people with autism. There’s many forms of it and many people look at it as not being able to talk, throwing fits, having difficulty walking, being built different, etc. Autism is so much more than that. There’s people you’d never guess are Autistic. Just because people don’t fit the ‘stereotype’ of an Autistic person, it doesn’t mean they aren’t. People need to see that anybody with Autism is just as good as any other person. Nobody is normal or perfect. Everyone is different in their own ways. People with Autism can do just as much as anyone else can. People have to just see and believe. 🙌🏼🥰

snippet.textDisplay:
Sensory overload is the biggest issue by far.

Sure there’s social problems like eye contact, misreading social cues, and not being able to automatically understand jokes as jokes.

I grew up abused and neglected becouse my parents didn’t understand why I acted different from my siblings.

Shocking absolutely nobody, I grew up scared of people and used to completely withdraw from others. I’m 21 and I still have mental breakdowns when I feel targeted.

I know it’s irrational and I understand my behaviors abnormal but nothing in my power can correct it. Mental therapy, further educating, speech therapy, and medication have no impact on my issues.

It really sucks to have daily migraines, uncontrollable thoughts, and the fear of making a mockery of myself.

(Such as the rather annoying example of how I always turn every sentence into an opinion instead of putting out there an actually interesting question or two.)

snippet.textDisplay:
Warning: WALL O' TEXT
As an Autistic person (With Aspergers & ADHD) I was pretty much treated the same way when I grew up (im 25 now), Im happy to see this video and I can really relate I'd tell the same things, I always had an indifferent interest in math/programming & art & manga/anime & storywriting myself I was bullied in school all the time, had no friends, and people would always find me wierd and nerdy calling me things, even physically abuse me, autism isn't a disorder its just a social difference, and the outer appearance or social skills doesn't reflect how a person is on the inside, but don't worry im good and happy now folks, I don't need many friends to be happy (unless u like the same things as me but wat are the chances then i'd love to!) but I hope I can enlighten some people by sharing my experience.

I see it as a blessing cause it made me who i am, now I am able to provide to society positively with economics, math, programming and as hobby even narrative art projects for niche audiances and help friends and family in ways noone else can cause of my traits, I probably wouldn't be this way and like those "boring things" (as most people seem to think they are) if I didnt have autism. Sure it gives me a hard time being around "normal/most" people but so what, everyones different and it's that simple. Everyone should accept each other as they are, NOT try to change them.

Alot of talented people are autistic, Different type of personalities is needed for us to evolve as a society, I just wanted to get that out there.. If everyone we're the same we wouldn't get anywhere... For example it's more common for programmers to be autistic cause of thinking more analytical rather than "social" and for me it's easier to communicate and be social with those "nerdy" people. I think it sucks people in this category have to go through so much BS cause of simple being "different", so what if I don't wanna waste my weekends on boring parties, getting drunk and losing braincells? different strokes for different folks, you do you, i do me

snippet.textDisplay:
This is amazing. It's great to see influential people speak up about things like this; the copious amount of misinformation and stigmatization around ASD is astounding, and it warms my heart to see people that are genuinely interested in learning about it. I was diagnosed with Tourettes, a condition on the spectrum, at 9.

We're so often discarded and thought of as people who can't do anything, but we're just as capable as anyone else is about anything. The worst part is that most of the mistreatment isn't intentional. It's based on misinformation and ignorance.
Thank you for this. It's really appreciated.

snippet.textDisplay: I am also on the spectrum, I have Asperger’s syndrome and ADHD, I’m grateful for my mom because she’s the reason I’ve become good at socializing; I still have trouble with it time to time. Not many people know I have autism cuz I’m higher functioning. But for me I focused on art and music, and maintaining eye contact use to be really hard but now I test myself how long I can keep eye contact. I also like that girl have anxiety disorder, towards junior and senior year it got worse it not only was just panicked attacks but I started getting painful stomach aches due to anxiety and stress. My school (not my teachers but the people in charge of disability shit) refused to give me an IEP  and went on to say my mom was a liar and  said I didn’t have autism. I had to get an advocate and even with her I wasn’t able to get what I needed. But my teachers were in my side through it all, supporting me, & help pushing me to succeed. And you know what I survived high school and graduated on time because of them. I really am thankful for my mom, friends and teachers.

snippet.textDisplay: This interview made me tear up. As a mom of an amazing little man with Autism. I love how you approached this so openly and didnt react like it was something that needed to be fixed. I know my little guy will have some many more hurdles to go through as he gets older and I hope he will be just as amazing as the wonderful people you interviewed. Thank you for spreading awareness. 💙
